His book highlights how much he enjoyed seeing deployed Aggies in Iraq and Afghanistan while he was Sec Def - many of whom he saw graduate and commission while he was President at Texas A&M. A great American who has truly served his country well. Grade, Elkhart Elementary School, Aurora, Colorado. I still remember vividly my first grade teacher being called out of class, then returning a few minutes later crying - something as first graders we had never seen before. She was the one who told us that President Kennedy had been shot, and that we would be going home soon. Not long afterward, the busses showed up and we were all sent home to hear the news that President Kennedy had died. As a 6 year old it was hard to fathom just how big a moment in our country's history this was, but I never forgot that day the rest of my life. I have no idea how our history would have changed had this tragic event not happened, but I can truly say it had a big impact on our lives at the time. Corps of Cadets, as a result of a traffic accident Monday evening in College Station. Caleb was a junior University Studies major in the College of Liberal Arts from Sequin and served as the Training Sergeant for Company P-2. He was pursuing a Navy contract. All who knew Caleb remember him as a sociable, confident young man who had a resilient work ethic and a good sense of humor. Out of 100 shooters:\n -Cadet Zach Williams finished fourth with a 1hr18 minute overall time.\n -Cadet Jordan Walker finished eight with a 1 hr 28 min overall time.\n -Cadet Tyler Toppenberg finished tenth with a 1 hr 25 minute overall time.\n -Cadet Bryan Bonnette finished twenty third with a 1 hr 29 minute overall time. \nVery proud of our cadets in the Corps Marksmanship Unit and their outstanding performance last weekend. Well done by all! Reveille is truly special to the Corps of Cadets, as she has been part of the Corps from the beginning. Reveille lives with the Corps every day in Company E-2, attends classes with the mascot handler from Company E-2, and marches with the Corps at all march-ins and parades. As the highest ranking member of the Corps of Cadets, Reveille is the only bearer of five silver diamonds in the entire Corps.\r\n\r\nReveille VII took over official duties from Reveille VI at Final Review in May, 2001, and served as Texas A&M's mascot through the end of the spring semester in 2008.\r\n\r\nSpecial thanks go out to Tina and Paul Gardner \u201966 for their love and care of Reveille VII since her retirement. She lived out her years in a safe, comfortable, and loving environment in their home in College Station, just as she deserved. C-Company and C-Battery will have a joint ceremony at 10 a.m. on Friday, August 23 and Squadron 4 will hold their ceremony at 11 a.m. on Saturday August 24. Each ceremony will include the unit activation ceremony and remarks from the Commandant of the Corps, unit commanders and former unit members. Both ceremonies will be followed by a reception inside the Sanders Corps Center for current cadets and former students. \r\n\r\nFor 137 years, the Texas A&M University Corps of Cadets has been producing leaders of character and preserving Aggie traditions. The individual units in the Corps have developed their own unique histories and traditions while maintaining a solid, united union of the Corps of Cadets.\r\n\r\nThroughout Corps history, various units have stood down for differing reasons \u2014 gone, but never forgotten \u2014 especially by their former members, eager to see their beloved units restored.\r\n\r\nIn 2012, the decision was made to reactivate two units, Squadron 1 and Company F-1. Last year, the decision was made to reactivate two additional units, Squadron 6 and Company S-2, to accommodate the steady growth of incoming students eager to be part of the storied Corps of Cadets.  There are plans to reactivate more units in the near future as the Corps continues to grow and the need to have more units increases.\r\n\r\n\u201cOver the past two years, we have reactivated four units, all of which have done well and are thriving again. With the Corps growing every year (we project almost 2,500 cadets for this fall semester, the largest in over 40 years) one priority is to ensure we have the proper place for all of them. I am very pleased to add these three additional units, C-Company and C-Battery, part of our 460-member Aggie Band, and Squadron 4, to the ranks of the Corps of Cadets as well,\u201d said Brigadier General Joe E. Ramirez, Jr. \u201979, commandant of the Corps. \u201cThey are a part of our Corps history and will be a new source of pride for our current cadets. The former cadets who were members of these units will be pleased to see their guidons once again flying on campus. By reactivating units with a history and tradition that is already a part of Texas A&M, we bring the past and the present together.\u201d\r\n\r\nThe Commander of C-Company will be Joshua Hewett \u201914. The Executive Officer will be Peter Schneider \u201914, and the 1st Sergeant will be Justin Tash \u201915. The Commander of C-Battery will be Steven Hankins \u201914. The Executive Officer will be Robert Hartmann \u201914, and the 1st Sergeant will be Christopher Martin \u201915. The Commander of Squadron 4 will be Daniel Lengyl \u201914. "created_time": "2013-06-10T17:07:36+0000", "message": "It is with extreme sadness that I confirm the death of Lieutenant Colonel Todd Clark '94 in Afghanistan this past weekend. Todd was a Fightin' Texas Aggie Class of \u201994 and a proud member of Company B-2 in the Corps of Cadets. He had a distinguished 17-year career in the U.S. Army, most recently as a brigade-level advisor with the Army's 10th Mountain Division. Todd served three tours in Iraq and was on his second tour in Afghanistan when he was killed. In July 2010, Todd received a Purple Heart for injuries sustained by a roadside bomb in Kandahar and spent his recovery at Walter Reed, becoming deeply involved in the Wounded Warrior program. I share the sentiment left on his Facebook page by a friend that Todd was a: \"Loving Husband and Father. Great Son. Leader. Mentor. Wounded Warrior ... Our Hero. Our Friend. Our Role Model.\" A fitting description and tribute to a great man. After this last tour in Afghanistan, Todd was going to return to Aggieland in the fall to serve as Executive Officer in the Texas A&M Army ROTC program, a job he described as his \u201cdream job.\u201d The Office of the Commandant and the Corps of Cadets offer their sincere condolences to Todd\u2019s wife Shelley, his children Madison and Collin, his parents Jack and Kathleen, his fellow B-2 classmates, and his extended family and friends. Todd makes the 29th Aggie and former member of the Corps of Cadets to have died in military service since 9/11 \u2013 something we should never forget. We will provide information on funeral arrangements as they become available. May God Bless Todd and his family, and may we never forget his sacrifice for our country and our freedoms. Rest in peace, Todd. We in the Corps of Cadets are especially fond of Reveille, as she has been part of the Corps from the beginning, lives with the Corps every day as a member of Company E-2, marches with the Corps at all march-ins and parades, and is the highest ranking member of the Corps of Cadets. We will remember with great fondness all the joy that Reveille VII brought to all Aggies during her time as our mascot, and will remember her excited barks every time our football team scored a touchdown. We know that she will continue to do so in the future as she joins the other Reveilles in the North end of Kyle Field where she will always be able to see the scoreboard and bark for her team. It is our most cherished of traditions, going back over a century. The muster of those who died is called, and an Aggie answers \"Here\" for their fallen fellow Aggie when their name is called. Over 300 Aggie Musters will be held worldwide today. I have personally held Aggie Muster in places like Kuwait, South Korea, Germany, and Iraq. This is a photo of probably the most famous Aggie Muster, held on Corregidor in the Philippines right after WWII to commemorate the Aggie Muster held at the Malinta Tunnel on Corregidor shortly before it fell to the Japanese at the outset of WWII. This is the classic World War II \"Pink and Greens\" Class A coat that many of us wore when we were in the Corps, and we will NOT do away with it nor replace it with another coat. I highly recommend you dress comfortably, wear sunscreen, hats, & sunglasses, bring umbrellas, lawn chairs, and plenty of water for the Corps of Cadets Review on Friday evening and for the Corps March-in on Saturday. Just a reminder on times: Corps Review is Friday evening at 5:30 PM on Simpson Drill Field. Cadets will step-off from the Quad at 5 PM. The Corps will step-off the Quad to march into Kyle Field for game day Saturday afternoon at 1 PM. Again, it'll be hot on the quad and all along the route to the stadium, so prepare accordingly! We have already conducted an After Action Review to discuss how we can do things better next year, but again, I'm happy to discuss with you if you wish to contact me about it. (979) 845-2811.", "id": "353307378040495_4053843", "user_likes": false}]}}

Eisenhower President of the United States.  Coupled along with his Inauguration speech it was one of the most, if not the most stirring ceremonies I have ever heard.\n\nAs an ordinary soldier or as many phrase it, just cannon fodder, I have a lot of gripes about the Army and the way things are being run over here.  Some of my gripes are justified, but most are not.  However, this is irrelevant to what I want to say.\n\nThe President's inaugural address has biven me new strength and courage to face the insecure future that confronts my generation.  Now I believe our country will go forward and estabilish the leadership and unity which the free world needs and must have.\n\nAs one among the rank and file of our Armed Forces I can sincerely state, that if it takes my life here or someshere else to accomplish this I will gladly lay it down upon the altar of Freedom.  The sounds of the guns tonight have a new meaning.  I know that I make no mistake in saying this.\n\nTo you, this may all sound a bit, shall we say, melodramatic.  But the times require more than lip service to freedom and the ravings of that breed called isolationists. I believe I realize more than most men just how close the world stands on the abyss of total slavery.  May God spare us that.\n\nThe President all but said in so many words that the decision is up to the American people.  I pray God that you will wake up in time and pull your head out of the sand before it is too late.  \n\nIf we muff this chance, our last chance, we will not only be in the chains of communist slavery, but the rest of the free work-world and all mankind.  God has never before granted such a responsibility of any one people.  Let us all, in uniform or out, not shirk in this trust or fail in this responsibility.\n\nDad I received your latest package and as usual I thank you.  Also Mother, I received your last box of Christmas cookies and they were as always superb.\n\nDon't get too worked up over my rotation as I might not start for home until March judging by way things are shaping up.\n\nYour loving son, \n\nFritz.", "id": "270990442938702_3524374", "user_likes": false}]}, "caption": "www.youtube.com", "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link":
